{{for|Master of Arts in Theology|Master of Arts}}
[[File:Benozzo Gozzoli 004a.jpg|thumb|[[Thomas Aquinas]], a 13th-century Christian theologian best known for his classic ''[[Summa Theologica]]'']]

In North America, the '''Master of Theology''' ({{lang-la|Theologiae Magister}}, abbreviated '''ThM''') is a post graduate or doctoral degree considered by the [[Association of Theological Schools]] to be the minimum educational credential for teaching theological subjects in accredited seminaries and graduate schools. The ThM is equivalent to the [[Master of Sacred Theology]] and the [[Association of Theological Schools]] classifies both degrees as "Advanced Programs Oriented Toward Theological Research and Teaching."<ref>{{cite web|title=Degree Program Standards|url=https://www.ats.edu/uploads/accrediting/documents/degree-program-standards.pdf|website=ATS|publisher=Association of Theological Schools|accessdate=18 January 2018}}</ref>

==North America==
A '''Master of Theology''' (ThM) is an advanced theological research degree offered by [[universities]], [[divinity school]]s, and [[seminaries]].<ref name="autogenerated1">{{citation|url=http://www.ats.edu/MemberSchools/Pages/Degrees.aspx|title=ATS - Approved Degrees|publisher=[[Association of Theological Schools in the United States and Canada]]|accessdate=2012-12-08}}</ref> The degree is usually earned after the [[Master of Divinity]] (MDiv) or an equivalent of three years of graduate studies in theology. This degree can range from one or two years of specialized advanced studies in theological research (i.e. Counseling, Church History, Systematic Theology, etc.). It may or may not require comprehensive subject exams and a research thesis, but is required to produce "learning outcomes that demonstrate advanced competency in one area or discipline of theological study and capacity to conduct original research in that area."<ref>{{cite web|title=Degree Program Standards|url=https://www.ats.edu/uploads/accrediting/documents/degree-program-standards.pdf|website=ATS|publisher=Association of Theological Schools|accessdate=18 January 2018}}</ref> The Master of Theology is usually designed as an advanced academic degree with an emphasis on academic research.  The ThM often functions as a terminal and/or doctoral level degree, dependent upon one's particular educational route or institution of study.<ref name="autogenerated1"/><ref>See {{citation|url=http://www.asburyseminary.edu/admissions/apply/apply-advanced-research-programs/|title=Advanced Research Programs (Th.M., Ph.D.)|publisher=[[Asbury Theological Seminary]]|accessdate=2012-12-08|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121113213722/http://www.asburyseminary.edu/admissions/apply/apply-advanced-research-programs/|archivedate=2012-11-13|df=}} and {{citation|url=http://divinity.duke.edu/academics/degrees/master-theology|title=Master of Theology (Th.M.)|publisher=[[Duke University]]|accessdate=2012-12-08}} for examples.</ref> Some institutions award a ThM en route to a [[Doctor of Philosophy]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Doctor of Philosophy|url=http://www.sbts.edu/doctoral/doctor-of-philosophy/|website=SBTS|publisher=Southern Baptist Theological Seminary|accessdate=18 January 2018}}</ref> or [[Doctor of Theology]] in addition offering stand alone ThM programs.

